article.description: Freshman Erlana Larkins found out just minutes before tipoff Sunday that she would make her first start for North Carolina (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 5 AP).
article.headline: Carolina has little trouble rebounding from loss
article.linkText: Larkins with 17 and 7 in first start for UNC
article.story:
CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- Freshman Erlana Larkins found out just minutes before tipoff Sunday that she would make her first start for North Carolina (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 5 AP).

She had a tougher time fighting off her own nerves than any Coastal Carolina defender.

Larkins had 17 points and seven rebounds to lift the Tar Heels past the Chanticleers 94-52, the latest in a series of strong performances for the 6-foot-2 forward.

Camille Little had 18 points to lead five players in double figures for the Tar Heels (8-1), who had no trouble rebounding from their first loss of the season. Ivory Latta scored 15 points, while La'Tangela Atkinson added 13 points and 12 rebounds.

The Tar Heels hadn't played since last week's 77-71 loss at Penn State, which dropped them from the No. 2 ranking -- the highest in school history. They sure had an easy time moving on, shooting 55 percent and taking a 43-29 rebounding edge.

Defensively, the Tar Heels used their athleticism and size to pressure the Chanticleers (2-3) all over the court. Coastal Carolina shot just 34 percent and committed 30 turnovers, while the Tar Heels blocked six shots and had 25 steals.

But Larkins -- nerves and all -- was the story.

She went 7-for-9 from the field, hit all three of her free throws and added three steals and three blocks in 21 minutes. She came in averaging 14 points and six rebounds and scored in double figures for the ninth time in as many games.

For the season, she's shooting 47-for-64 (73 percent) from the field and 36-for-40 from the line.

"She's strong in there, got good hands and is a good shooter," North Carolina coach Sylvia Hatchell said. "She's the real deal, I keep saying that about her. She gives us a real strong presence inside."

Larkins got the start in place of senior guard Leah Metcalf, who sat out to rest a sore foot.

"I didn't know what to say," Larkins said of learning she would start. "I was nervous, actually. I just feel better coming off the bench."

Little -- last year's ACC rookie of the year -- went a step further.

"She was shaking in her boots," Little said with a laugh.

Larkins wasted no time making herself comfortable in the starting five. She had the game's first basket barely 11 seconds in and scored 10 points on 5-for-5 shooting in the first five minutes.

Larkins had two baskets off offensive rebounds and a nice pass on a give-and-go layup by Latta in that span.

Leading 20-10, North Carolina put Coastal Carolina away with a 26-8 run over the next nine minutes. The Tar Heels scored just about every way possible, from reserve Jessica Sell scoring a layup off a turnover in the backcourt to two 3-pointers -- one a pull-up in
transition -- from the 5-6 Latta.

At one point during the spurt, Coastal Carolina ended seven straight possessions with either a turnover or missed shot.

Atkinson's layup off a feed from Sell with 2:02 left in the half ended the run, giving the Tar Heels a 46-18 lead. North Carolina led by 22 at halftime and pushed the margin to 42 in the final minute.

"They keep you from getting in your offense," Coastal Carolina coach Alan LeForce said. "We just panicked. We played with no poise. We'd catch the ball and as soon as we'd catch it, we'd want to get rid of it. But they'd be there shooting the gap to get the
ball and get layups at the other end."

Demaria Young had 16 points for the Chanticleers.
